/* ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

HEXCRAWL GENERATOR 1.0

A hexcrawl game is a type of tabletop role-playing or board game where 
a player explore a map divided into hexagonal tiles (or "hexes"). Each 
hex may represent a distinct area, such as a forest, mountain, or desert, 
and typically each contains unique encounters, challenges, or resources.

In this game, a players navigate the hexes, often without full knowledge 
of what lies ahead, making discovery a central theme. Encounters, events, 
or terrain features can mix randomly determined and pre-generated 
encounters for each hex. The player must consider travel times, terrain 
difficulty, and resources as they decide where to go next. Hexcrawls often 
lack a linear plot, allowing players to explore freely and shape their own 
adventures, but series of encounters may also string together into a 
common theme or growing narrative.

The code below uses PHP, a hypertext preprocessor script widely open
source used mainly for webpage development. PHP can be edited in a simple
text or code editor on various operating systems, including Linux, Windows,
or macOS, and it runs seamlessly with popular servers like Apache and Nginx.
The script does not need to be compiled in any way to be used. PHP scripts 
execute on a web server and, using the HTML template set up at the final 
"echo" command, return a dynamic and interactive webpage.

Example: Write and save a file named "helloworld.php," upload it to a
web server running PHP, and call the page from:
http://(your domain name)/helloworld.php

<?php
echo "Hello, World!";
?>

The script should display the worlds "Hello, World!" in a web browser.

This script assumes at least three files are needed...

* intro.php -- slides to set tone, rules, character creation choices
* play.php -- the core "engine" of the dynamic webpage
* play.css -- the stylesheet used to help position and color text and images

A game designer can customize this script by filling in variables noted
by a dollar sign, or sometimes formatted in an array of variables to save
space in the script...

$hexName = "The Lair of the Dragon";
$names = array("Conan", "Elric", "Merlin", "Morgan le Fay", "Gandalf");
$name = $names[3] // name will be set to "Morgan le Fay"

Another trick used throughout this PHP script is generate a random number
and use it to select the value of a variable. For example, here there is
no value to "oath" until the script generates a number to select which
text should update the variable. This option format is less compact and 
efficient but can be easier to read when reviewing the text of responses.
Previously defined variables may also be inserted into the string/text of
an option, as shown here with "$name" for the name choosen by the player.

$oath = "";
$oathPick = mt_rand(1,5);
if ($oathPick == "1") {$oath = "A wizard is never late, nor is he early.";}
elseif ($oathPick == "2") {$oath = "The flower that blooms in adversity is the most rare and beautiful of all.";}
elseif ($oathPick == "3") {$oath = "This is my boomstick!";}
elseif ($oathPick == "4") {$oath = "Do or do not. There is no try.";}
elseif ($oathPick == "5") {$oath = "Hello. My name is $name. You killed my father. Prepare to die.";}

Random choices may also be based off range bands, such as 1 to 3 out of 6
means "option A," 4 or 5 means "option B," and 6 means "option C." 

$starship = "";
$starshipPick = mt_rand(1, 100);
if ($starshipPick >= "0") {$starship = "USS Enterprise";}
if ($starshipPick >= "20") {$starship = "Millennium Falcon";}
if ($starshipPick >= "35") {$starship = "Nostromo";}
if ($starshipPick >= "66") {$starship = "Serenity";}
if ($starshipPick >= "82") {$starship = "Discovery One";}

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ */

