/* ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

THE HEXCRAWL MAP

The virtual gameboard is, obviously, meant to be a clusters of
encounter locations next to each other in the shape of six-sides
hexagrams - or, rather, a grid in which each column is offset by
half the height of the squares in its adjoining left and right 
columns. Hexagonal grids allow for equal player movement in all 
directions, unlike square grids with diagonal movement inconsistencies.
Hexes support modularity, making game boards easier to randomize or 
expand. Finally, hexes look aesthetically pleasing and are often 
associated with natural patterns, like beehives, which resonate 
with themes of strategy and connectivity.

One of most famous example of this sort of game board is found 
in 1995's "Settlers of Catan," where modular hexagon tiles 
represent different terrain types (e.g., forests, hills, mountains).

The hex may be represent a physical location or something more
abstract. Hexes are used to organize potential encounters the
player may choose to experience by moving across this board.

In order for this code to help keep track of player's location
on this expanse, each hex is given a hex number ID, typically
starting with 1000000 - the "number one million" space. This number
allows for the player to have up to 50,000 moves in any direction
before running out of playable virtual space.

The following code allows the game designer to display the name
of neighboring hexes in the navigation picker the player uses in
the "move" phase in each encounter. If destinations are meant to
be unknown, delete the function and replace it with something
along these lines:

$hexN = "North";
$hexNE = "Northeast";
$hexSE = "Southeast";
$hexS = "South";
$hexSW = "Southwest";
$hexNW = "Northwest";

~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~ */

/* If game state requires movement as the player's options,
change variables for navigation selector... */

